      content: `<div class="lesson-content"><h1>AI Ethics Framework</h1><h2>What You'll Learn</h2><p>Build a practical ethics framework for AI deployment ‚Äî understanding bias, ensuring fairness, and making responsible decisions.</p><h2>Why AI Ethics Matter for Business</h2><pre style="background: rgba(239,68,68,0.1); padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #ef4444;">Real consequences of ignoring AI ethics:\n‚Ä¢ Amazon's AI hiring tool was scrapped for gender bias\n‚Ä¢ AI chatbots have generated racist and offensive content\n‚Ä¢ AI-generated deepfakes have caused reputational damage\n‚Ä¢ Biased AI in lending has led to discrimination lawsuits\n\nThe cost of getting it wrong:\n‚Ä¢ Legal liability\n‚Ä¢ Brand reputation damage\n‚Ä¢ Customer trust erosion\n‚Ä¢ Regulatory penalties</pre><h2>The FAIR Framework for AI Ethics</h2><pre style="background: rgba(59,130,246,0.1); padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6;">F ‚Äî Fairness\n‚Ä¢ Does the AI treat all groups equitably?\n‚Ä¢ Are there biases in the training data or outputs?\n‚Ä¢ Test with diverse scenarios and demographics\n\nA ‚Äî Accountability\n‚Ä¢ Who is responsible when AI makes a mistake?\n‚Ä¢ Is there a clear chain of oversight?\n‚Ä¢ Can decisions be explained and justified?\n\nI ‚Äî Inclusivity\n‚Ä¢ Does the AI work for people with disabilities?\n‚Ä¢ Are diverse perspectives represented?\n‚Ä¢ Does it work across languages and cultures?\n\nR ‚Äî Reliability\n‚Ä¢ Is the AI output consistent and predictable?\n‚Ä¢ Are there safeguards against harmful outputs?\n‚Ä¢ Is there human oversight for critical decisions?</pre><h2>Bias in AI: What to Watch For</h2><pre style="background: rgba(0,0,0,0.3); padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">Types of AI bias:\n\n1. Training data bias\n   AI reflects biases in its training data.\n   If trained on biased hiring data ‚Üí biased hiring recommendations\n\n2. Representation bias\n   Certain groups are underrepresented in training data.\n   AI may perform worse for these groups.\n\n3. Confirmation bias amplification\n   AI can reinforce existing beliefs rather than challenging them.\n   Echo chambers become algorithmically amplified.\n\n4. Automation bias\n   Humans over-trust AI decisions.\n   "The AI said so, it must be right."\n\nMitigation strategies:\n‚Ä¢ Test AI outputs across diverse scenarios\n‚Ä¢ Never use AI as the sole decision-maker for high-stakes decisions\n‚Ä¢ Regularly audit AI outputs for patterns of bias\n‚Ä¢ Include diverse perspectives in AI deployment decisions</pre><h2>Practical Ethics Checklist</h2><pre style="background: rgba(16,185,129,0.1); padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #10b981;">Before deploying any AI system, ask:\n\n‚ñ° Could this harm anyone? (individuals or groups)\n‚ñ° Is there bias in the training data or outputs?\n‚ñ° Who is accountable if something goes wrong?\n‚ñ° Is there human oversight for critical decisions?\n‚ñ° Are we transparent about AI use?\n‚ñ° Do users know they're interacting with AI?\n‚ñ° Can someone opt out of AI-driven decisions?\n‚ñ° Are we handling data responsibly?\n‚ñ° Have we tested with diverse scenarios?\n‚ñ° Do we have a plan for when AI fails?</pre><h2>Key Takeaways</h2><ol><li><strong>Ethics are a business imperative</strong> ‚Äî not just moral obligation</li><li><strong>FAIR framework:</strong> Fairness, Accountability, Inclusivity, Reliability</li><li><strong>Bias is inevitable</strong> ‚Äî the question is how you identify and mitigate it</li><li><strong>Human oversight</strong> is essential for high-stakes AI decisions</li><li><strong>Use the ethics checklist</strong> before every AI deployment</li></ol><h2>Coming Up Next</h2><p>Lesson 11.2 covers AI Legal & Compliance ‚Äî copyright, data privacy, and regulatory requirements.</p></div>`,
